  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent and report money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Maintaining detailed customer records\n\n2. Suspicious Activity Reporting\n- Identifying and reporting suspicious transactions\n- Filing reports with financial crime enforcement agencies\n- Monitoring unusual financial patterns\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance programs\n- Developing internal policies and procedures\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n- Training employees on detection and prevention\n\n4. Transaction monitoring\n- Tracking large or unusual financial transactions\n- Reporting cash transactions above certain thresholds\n- Maintaining detailed transaction records\n\n5. International compliance\n- Following global standards like FATF recommendations\n- Cooperating with international financial crime investigations\n- Implementing cross-border transaction controls\n\n6. Penalties for non-compliance\n- Significant financial fines\n- Potential criminal charges\n- Loss of banking licenses\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent criminal financial activities and protect the integrity of the financial system.",
